June 30=2C 2025

Question:
Comment 1. Clearly=2C while your world insights eclipse most anyone=E2=80=
=99s I encourage you to not fall into the hate Donald Trump Club by making=
 him look erratic undisciplined.

Comment 2. You have described a complex and well considered strategy on di=
plomacy. Trump is not bright enough for what you describe.

Response:
I have placed these two comments side by side=2C one thinking I have made=
 Trump look bad=2C and the other saying that I have made him look too smar=
t.

First the direct answer. Early in my career I realized that being an analy=
st is incompatible with being partisan. Over time I came to what is perhap=
s a more sophisticated understanding=2C which is that elections are not ba=
sed on voters=E2=80=99 views but that views are determined by the massive=
 historical forces that shape human thought and generate those opinions. S=
ince different people experience those forces in different ways=2C we wind=
 up with different people having different views of the same thing. If you=
 can understand the impersonal forces of economics=2C geopolitics and the=
 rest=2C you can understand and to some extent predict the options that ar=
e open=2C and understand the way that opinions are shaped and divided betw=
een nations=2C within nations and between people.

Therefore=2C it is not surprising that one person should caution me to not=
 underestimate Trump=2C and another to not overestimate him. The comments=
 above are consolidations of two commonly held views representing the divi=
sion of the nation on Trump. I have written in some books (The Storm Befor=
e the Calm) and articles on the forces leading to the intensity of this di=
vision=2C which doesn=E2=80=99t fit into the space available here=2C but f=
rom my point of view this divided feeling of the two comments demonstrates=
 the health of our democracy.

The foundation of democracy is not only that the citizens ultimately gover=
n=2C but that the citizens are and should be divided. Tyrannies emerge fro=
m societies where there is an overwhelming consensus that crushes diversit=
y. A healthy democracy avoids tyranny partly because of a divided populati=
on and the constant evolution of belief. So read by one citizen=2C my arti=
cle seems to be based on admiration for the president=2C the other sees it=
 based on loathing.  It is this division that guarantees a democratic soci=
ety.

I have lived long enough to remember the love and loathing of many preside=
nts. Sentiment surrounding Lyndon Johnson Richard Nixon was no less divide=
d or intense than the sentiment surrounding Trump.  When we accuse Trump o=
f wanting to be a dictator=2C we are levelling an accusation that many pre=
sidents since the founding have faced. From my point of view=2C Trump has=
 twice been elected by the majority of voters. He=2C more than most candid=
ates=2C did not make an attempt to hide his personality or his core belief=
s. He was elected=2C and the people have spoken. For me=2C the social and=
 economic forces of America and the world caused his election.  His majori=
ty is kept in check by the vigorous loathing of him and the deep belief by=
 many that his presidency is dangerous and in some way illegitimate. That=
 powerful sense shapes and defines his presidency and reflects a deep divi=
sion that has developed in America and is a healthy process in a democracy=
 in which any candidate for president has this in common
with all presidents: a large ego that allows him to believe that he should=
 govern the Republic. And in this=2C a good analyst is always distrusted b=
y both sides.
Question: You have made comments in the past about the felicitous position=
 of the United States between two militarily weak nations [Mexico=2C Cana=
da] with no axes to grind. Why would Trump mess this up?

Response: Nations always have issues between each other. What is peculiar=
 is the degree to which the United States and particularly Canada=2C and t=
o a lesser extent Mexico=2C had few such issues. This is not the norm (a t=
erm I hate) of relations between countries. The emergence of significant i=
ssues between countries=2C particularly neighbors=2C is returning to the n=
orm. So I am more amazed by the lack of tension than by its presence. I al=
so believe that this is a passing phase of a nation in the process of shif=
ting its position in the world; weaker neighbors are stunned and angered b=
y such shifts. Mexico and Canada will adjust to the changes and the newly=
 created reality simply because neither is strong enough to resist its gia=
nt neighbor.
Question: How does Trump operate once a negotiation is accomplished? Does=
 he stay a provocateur or become a trusted partner in joint success?

Response: International relations are constantly changing because the real=
ities inside countries are constantly shifting. Previous agreements are th=
erefore changed=2C even abandoned. It is extraordinary that the American r=
elationship with Western Europe remained fairly stable for 80 years=2C and=
 it is reasonable that the Europeans wanted that to continue and the Unite=
d States wanted to redefine it. So will Trump honor his agreements? He wil=
l until he deems it not in American interest to do so=2C as will the natio=
ns he made deals with. It=E2=80=99s kind of like marriages. They last as l=
ong as husband and wife both wish it to. Nations are human institutions=2C=
 and the marriage might last or not.
The Discussion Continues - George=E2=80=99s answers to last week=E2=80=99s=
 follow up questions.
Question/Comment: Regarding lobbyists and corporations =E2=80=93 While I a=
gree to the fact that it is part of democracy=2C wealthy people and corpor=
ations seem to have no limits to campaign contributions. And when super PA=
Cs are used=2C we don't even know who contributed=2C how much they contrib=
uted or who it went to. Campaign finance reform only remains popular among=
 the losing parties. What are your thoughts on the need for campaign finan=
ce reform and what it would take to get such reforms ushered in?

Response: Campaign contributions allow for the purchase of advertisements.=
 I am not  certain when the last time was that I watched television. We ow=
n a couple=2C but we look at Netflix movies=2C or DVDs=2C or read books. I=
 am not certain that television ads matter much anymore=2C or that many pe=
ople are buying newspapers with political advertisements with them. Today=
=2C social media and online publications like mine are the norm. So the ol=
d model is not as essential. I guess money is needed for travel expenses=
=2C but I would suspect that we are now in an ideological period in which=
 voters have pre-packaged beliefs=2C or are influenced more online than wi=
th money. I am not certain on this=2C but I think the period of the last c=
entury where advertising was a critical element of elections is still in p=
lace=2C and elections are influenced by money. I am genuinely not sure abo=
ut this=2C and haven=E2=80=99t really thought about it=2C but this questio=
n caused me to wonder just how much influence money has in today=E2=80=99s=
 elections.
Comment/Question: You mentioned that Congress should make the decision to=
 go to war based on the Constitution. You also mentioned that modern war t=
echnologies allow only a few minutes for a reaction time. Our Constitution=
 requires such questions be addressed by Congress. What are the chances Co=
ngress could do so by updating the definition of a =E2=80=9Cdeclaration of=
 war=E2=80=9D? What could a possible new definition look like? When doing=
 so=2C please take into consideration how precedence set by Presidents (WP=
A=2C etc) do not define nor do they constrain the level of conflict in whi=
ch a president may engage.

Response: The definition of war is one nation attacking another=2C and sol=
diers killing each other. We have invented new names for war =E2=80=93 pea=
cekeeping=2C counterterrorism and the rest. We have decided that the invas=
ion of Grenada was not an act of war but something else that I don=E2=80=
=99t remember. When the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor=2C that was an act of=
 war. When we bombed Iran=2C that was an act of war. One of the fundamenta=
l problems we have today is that the surprise attack cannot start with a C=
ongressional debate=2C and when we went to war in Vietnam=2C a declaration=
 of war was not deemed to be appropriate=2C since American involvement sta=
rted small and then by its end 20 years later had taken 50=2C000 American=
 lives. So we need to develop a different process for going to war than wh=
at=E2=80=99s in the Constitution=2C which requires more than a presidentia=
l decision to go to war. There are several new laws that allow us to wage=
 war on a presidential order=2C but the reason I don=E2=80=99t like them i=
s that they run counter
to the Constitutional constraint=2C and that sets a precedent for other vi=
olations of the Constitution by the president.

